\033[38;2;59;66;97m┃\033[0m\033[38;2;86;95;137m It is not the general idea that is implicated in opposition and combat, and that is exposed to danger. It remains in the background, untouched and uninjured. This may be called the cunning of reason, – that it sets the passions to work for itself, while that which develops its existence through such impulsion pays the penalty and suffers loss.  Yet no lingering lies or make-believe strokes in the air can achieve anything against it. They can perhaps reach the shoelaces of this colossus, and smear on a bit of boot wax or mud, but they cannot untie the laces.\033[0m\\n- Hegel, Philosophy of History (1831)\n
\033[38;2;59;66;97m┃\033[0m\033[38;2;86;95;137m In Nature there happens ‘nothing new under the sun’.\033[0m\\n- Hegel, Philosophy of History (1831)\n
