\033[38;2;59;66;97m┃\033[0m\033[38;2;86;95;137m Anyone who doubts the inevitability of the dictatorship of the proletariat, as a necessary stage of its victory over the bourgeoisie, facilitates the conditions for the victory of the latter; anyone who doubts or renounces the political party of the proletariat, is helping to weaken and disorganize the working class.\033[0m\\n- Lev Kamenev, The Dictatorship of the Proletariat (1920)\n
\033[38;2;59;66;97m┃\033[0m\033[38;2;86;95;137m It is folly, not revolutionism, to deprive ourselves in advance of any freedom of action, openly to inform an enemy who is at present better armed than we are whether we shall fight him, and when. To accept battle at a time when it is obviously advantageous to the enemy, but not to us, is criminal; political leaders of the revolutionary class are absolutely useless if they are incapable of “changing tack, or offering conciliation and compromise” in order to take evasive action in a patently disadvantageous battle.\033[0m\\n- V.I. Lenin, Left-Wing Communism: an Infantile Disorder (1920)\n
\033[38;2;59;66;97m┃\033[0m\033[38;2;86;95;137m The popular masses who want peace, freedom and bread must, in this period of dark onrush of events, always hold themselves ready to spring up as one man against every danger of new carnage and suffering threatened by the so heroic exploits of fascism.\033[0m\\n- Antonio Gramsci, The development of fascism (1921)\n
\033[38;2;59;66;97m┃\033[0m\033[38;2;86;95;137m When wages have disappeared, when all are upon a basis of economic equality, when the position of manager, director, organiser, etc., brings no material advantage, the desire for it will be less widespread and less keen, and the danger of oppressive action by the management will be largely nullified. Nevertheless, management imposed on unwilling subordinates will not be tolerated; where the organiser has chosen the assistants, the assistants will be free to leave, or change him; where the assistants choose the organiser, they will be free to change him. Co-operation for the common good is necessary, but freedom, not domination, is the goal.\033[0m\\n- E. Sylvia Pankhurst, Communism and its Tactics (1921)\n
